ther than seeing the postwar period as the era of multiculturalism, So argues that we should understand it as the invention of a new form of racial inequality—one that continues to shape the arts and literature today.Interweaving data analysis of large-scale patterns with a consideration of Toni Morrison’s career as an editor at Random House and readings of individual works by Octavia Butler, Henry Dumas, Amy Tan, and others, So develops a form of criticism that brings together qualitative and quantitative approaches to the study of literature. A vital and provocative work for American literary studies, critical race studies, and the digital humanities, Redlining Culture shows the importance of data and computational methods for understanding and challenging racial inequality.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aAmerican fictionxAfrican American authorsxHistory and critcism. 0aAmerican fictionxAfrican American authorsxHistory and criticism. 0aAmerican fictiony20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aAuthors and publisherszUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aDiscrimination in employmentzUnited States 0aDiscrimination in employmentzUnited States. 0aLiterature and societyzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aLiterature publishingxPolitical aspectszUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aLiteraturexData processing. 0aRace discriminationzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Publishing.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertColumbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311073907708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020z9783110704518oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe Gruytert